  "bib_entries": {
    "144718068": {
      "title": "Inter-firm networks and entrepreneurial behavior: A structural embeddedness perspective",
      "abstract": "We develop a theory of the effects of inter-organizational networks on both radical and incremental forms of firm-level entrepreneurial behavior (EB). The central argument is that structural embeddedness, with its focus on the network as a whole, and its two consequences, relational and cognitive embeddedness, individually and collectively influence incremental and radical forms of EB. Relationships in our model are driven by reciprocal interactions between intra- and inter-organizational sensemaking. This reasoning leads us to a dynamic, co-evolutionary model of EB."
    },
    "44104098": {
      "title": "Do bridging ties complement strong ties? an empirical examination of alliance ambidexterity",
      "abstract": "This study examines the underexplored tensions and complementarities between bridging ties and strong ties in innovation-seeking alliances. Bridging ties span structural holes to provide innovation potential but lack integration capacity, and strong ties provide integration capacity but lack innovation potential. We theoretically develop the idea that - notwithstanding their tensions - strong ties complement bridging ties in enhancing alliance ambidexterity at the project level. While bridging ties provide access to diverse, structural hole-spanning perspectives and capabilities, strong ties help integrate them to realize an innovation. We also propose that their effects and complementarities influence alliance ambidexterity because they facilitate knowledge integration at the project level. Tests using data on 42 innovation-seeking, e-business project alliances involving a major American services conglomerate and its alliance partners support the majority of the proposed ideas. Implications for interfirm network configuration, strategic alliances, and the broader strategy literature are also discussed."
    },
    "26978983": {
      "title": "Niche and performance: The moderating role of network embeddedness",
      "abstract": "This article considers the relationship between niche and firm performance. Two types of niche are identified: product-niche (competitive position based on a distinctive product offering) and process-niche (competitive position based on distinctive operational processes).Data are drawn from 80 U.S. venture capital firms and their holdings in 369 initial public offerings covering the period 1995-98.Multiple archival sources were used to assess firm performance, product-niche, process-niche, and network embeddedness.The analysis indicates that product-niche and process-niche interact with network embeddedness to determine firm performance. The Impact of a product-niche depends on its embeddedness in the networks from which a firm obtains information to develop and market its products. The impact of a process-niche depends on the embeddedness in networks that protect the security of the process.Implications for management research and practice, as well as future research, are also discussed. (TNM)"
    }
  },
